d race differences. The book also looks at how LGBT movements in other nations have responded to the recognition of same-sex marriages, and what we might emulate or adjust in our own advocacy. Aiming to spark discussion and further debate regarding the challenges and possibilities of the LGBT movement’s future, After Marriage Equality will be of interest to anyone who cares about the future of sexual equality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aGay liberation movementzUnited States. 0aGay liberation movement. 0aSame-sex marriagezUnited States. 0aSame-sex marriage. 0aSexual minoritiesxCivil rightszUnited States. 0aSexual minoritiesxCivil rights. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Gay Studies.2bisacsh1 aBall, Carlos A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479883080.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479898794423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479898794/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles